.TH READSEEK 1 "2026-07-22" "readseek 0.8.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
readseek \- structural source and PDF reader with stable line hashing
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-h\fR|\fB--help\fR]
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-V\fR|\fB--version\fR]
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB--output\fR \fIpath\fR] [\fB--readseek-dir\fR \fIdir\fR] \fIcommand\fR ...

\fBreadseek detect\fR
    \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek read\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR|\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR] \fItarget\fR
\fBreadseek read\fR [\fB--vision-mode\fR \fBnone|all|caption|objects|ocr\fR]
    [\fB--vision-level\fR \fBlow|medium|high\fR] [\fB--page\fR \fIpage\fR] \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek view\fR [\fB--format\fR \fBplain|json\fR] [\fB--node\fR \fIid\fR]
    [\fB--page\fR \fIpage\fR] [\fB--kind\fR \fIkind\fR] [\fB--depth\fR \fIn\fR]
    [\fB--outline\fR] \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek map\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek check\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek symbol\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR [\fB--name\fR]

\fBreadseek identify\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR]
    \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek def\fR [\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR] [\fB\-g\fR|\fB--git\fR \fIscopes\fR]
    [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIname\fR

\fBreadseek refs\fR [\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR] [\fB--scope\fR \fB--line\fR \fIline\fR [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR]]
    [\fB\-g\fR|\fB--git\fR \fIscopes\fR]
    [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIname\fR

\fBreadseek rename\fR \fB--line\fR \fIline\fR [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR] \fB--to\fR \fIname\fR
    [\fB--workspace\fR \fIdir\fR] [\fB\-g\fR|\fB--git\fR \fIscopes\fR]
    [\fB--apply\fR] [\fB--plan-hash\fR \fIhash\fR]
    [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR] \fItarget\fR

\fBreadseek search\fR [\fB\-g\fR|\fB--git\fR \fIscopes\fR]
    [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIpattern\fR

\fBreadseek init\fR [\fIpath\fR]
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B readseek
outputs compact JSON for scripts, editors, and coding agents that need stable,
addressable source context.
.PP
Source lines are emitted as hashline records: a line number, a 3-character hash,
and the original text. Unchanged lines retain their hashes. Operational errors go
to standard error, so JSON output remains safe to pipe.

.SH INPUTS AND TARGETS

Most commands take a file or directory \fItarget\fR. The \fBdetect\fR, \fBread\fR,
\fBmap\fR, \fBcheck\fR, \fBsymbol\fR, and \fBidentify\fR commands accept standard input
when the target starts with \fBstdin:\fR. The remainder is an optional path used for
language detection and may include a line or hash address. For example,
\fBstdin:scratch.rs:42\fR detects Rust from the extension and selects line 42;
\fBstdin::42\fR falls back to content and shebang detection.
A target path may carry a suffix that selects a specific line:
.nf
.RS
\fIfile\fR:\fIline\fR
\fIfile\fR:\fIhash\fR
.RE
.fi
Line numbers are one-based. A hash suffix is a 3-character hash previously emitted
by \fBread\fR, \fBmap\fR, or \fBsearch\fR.

For \fBsymbol\fR, the \fB--name\fR flag treats the target suffix as a
qualified or unqualified symbol name. If the name matches more than one symbol,
the command reports an error.
.SH LANGUAGES

\fBreadseek\fR detects languages from file names, extensions, shebangs, and syntax.
Parsing commands accept \fB--language\fR to override detection.

The following language identifiers are accepted:
\fBassembly\fR,
\fBbash\fR,
\fBc\fR,
\fBcpp\fR,
\fBcsharp\fR,
\fBcss\fR,
\fBdockerfile\fR,
\fBgdscript\fR,
\fBgo\fR,
\fBhtml\fR,
\fBjava\fR,
\fBjavascript\fR,
\fBjson\fR,
\fBjsx\fR,
\fBjust\fR,
\fBkconfig\fR,
\fBlatex\fR,
\fBlua\fR,
\fBmake\fR,
\fBmarkdown\fR,
\fBmeson\fR,
\fBnix\fR,
\fBperl\fR,
\fBphp\fR,
\fBpuppet\fR,
\fBpython\fR,
\fBriscv\fR,
\fBruby\fR,
\fBrust\fR,
\fBsql\fR,
\fBswift\fR,
\fBtoml\fR,
\fBtsx\fR,
\fBtypescript\fR,
\fBtypst\fR,
\fBxml\fR,
\fByaml\fR,
\fBvimscript\fR, and
\fBzig\fR.
The special value \fBunknown\fR treats the input as plain text and disables any
parser-based features.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B detect
Print detection metadata as JSON. Source files include language and parser data;
images include format, dimensions, and animation status; PDFs include page count.
Unknown input uses \fBtext/plain\fR.
.TP
.B read
Print line numbers, hashes, and text. Without range options, the entire file is
returned. A line or hash target suffix sets the first line. \fB--end\fR selects the
last line (inclusive); \fB--limit\fR selects a count. They cannot be combined.
.IP
Visual files use a separate result shape. Images return bounded base64 by default;
\fB--vision-mode\fR selects all analyses or one of captioning, object detection, and OCR.
PDFs return page-tagged Markdown and embedded images using the same mode. The
\fIlow\fR level is the default; increase to \fImedium\fR or \fIhigh\fR only when
additional detail is needed. Vision options cannot be combined with \fB--end\fR,
\fB--limit\fR, or \fB--language\fR; line and hash suffixes do not apply. Analyzed
files use a lazily downloaded Qwen3-VL-2B Q8_0 model and multimodal projector with
ReadSeek's built-in CPU engine. Set \fBRUST_LOG=tracing\fR to emit cache and
inference traces on standard error.
.TP
.B view
Create or reuse a persistent PDF index and print a bounded view. A
\fI.readseek/\fR directory must exist; run \fBinit\fR or pass \fB--readseek-dir\fR.
With no selector, print an overview. Narrow it with \fB--page\fR, \fB--node\fR,
\fB--kind\fR, \fB--depth\fR, or \fB--outline\fR. Output is plain by default;
\fB--format json\fR emits the structured representation.
.TP
.B map
Print each extracted symbol's kind, name, qualified name, line range, boundary
hashes, byte span, and name-token offset. Unsupported languages return an empty
symbol list.
.TP
.B check
Print tree-sitter \fIERROR\fR and \fIMISSING\fR counts and locations. Languages
without a parser return zero counts and an empty list.
.TP
.B symbol
Print the source range for one symbol. With \fB--name\fR, the target suffix is
treated as a qualified or unqualified symbol name. Without \fB--name\fR, a line
or hash suffix selects the symbol containing that location.
.TP
.B identify
Print the selected line, its hash, the identifier at the cursor, and the enclosing
symbol. The default column is 1. Columns are one-based byte offsets. Parser-based
identifier lookup falls back to an ASCII identifier scan. JSON ranges include
one-based, inclusive-start/exclusive-end columns and exact byte offsets.
.TP
.B def
Find mapped symbol definitions in a file or directory. \fIname\fR may be qualified
or unqualified. Directory selection follows \fBsearch\fR. \fB--format plain\fR emits
quickfix-friendly locations instead of definition objects.
.TP
.B refs
Find identifier occurrences in a file or directory. Results include file, line,
column, line hash, text, and the enclosing symbol when available. Directory
selection follows \fBsearch\fR. \fB--format plain\fR flattens symbol metadata.
.IP
With \fB--scope\fR and a cursor location, restrict results to the lexical binding in
one file and label occurrences as \fBdefinition\fR or \fBreference\fR. Scope resolution
supports Rust, C, C++, Python, Go, Java, JavaScript, JSX, TypeScript, TSX, C#,
Swift, and Vim script. Other languages report no resolvable binding.
.TP
.B rename
Plan a binding-aware rename at the cursor. The plan includes names, conflicts, and
hash-anchored edits. Without \fB--apply\fR, no files are changed. Applying refuses
conflicts and stale line hashes before writing. The \fIapplied\fR field reports
whether changes were written. Rename supports the same languages as
\fBrefs --scope\fR.
.IP
\fB--workspace\fR extends the plan across a directory or repository. The cursor file
remains binding-aware; other files use name matching. Occurrences that resolve to
local declarations are excluded when the language supports bindings. Other
languages are matched by name. File selection honors the same Git flags as
\fBrefs\fR. All files are verified before writing; if a write fails, readseek
attempts to restore files already changed.
.TP
.B search
Run an AST pattern against a file or supported source files under a directory.
Unparseable and unsupported files are skipped. \fB$\fR\fINAME\fR matches one node;
\fB$$$\fR\fINAME\fR matches zero or more sibling nodes. Results are grouped by file
and include hashes, ranges, captures, and matched hashlines.
.TP
.B init
Create \fI.readseek/\fR under \fIpath\fR (the current directory by default), then
populate its map cache and definition index. Existing caches are refreshed.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
Print usage information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB--version\fR
Print the program version and exit.
.TP
\fB--output\fR \fIpath\fR
Write command output to \fIpath\fR instead of standard output. Not valid with
\fB--version\fR or \fBinit\fR.
.TP
\fB--readseek-dir\fR \fIdir\fR
Use \fIdir\fR instead of discovering \fI.readseek/\fR by walking up from the target.
This global option must precede the command. With \fBinit\fR, it selects where the
directory is created.
.TP
\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR
Force a specific language instead of auto-detection. See \fBLANGUAGES\fR above.
.TP
\fB--vision-mode\fR \fImode\fR
For \fBread\fR on images or PDFs: \fInone\fR (default, bounded base64), \fIall\fR,
\fIcaption\fR, \fIobjects\fR, or \fIocr\fR. See \fBread\fR under \fBCOMMANDS\fR.
.TP
\fB--vision-level\fR \fIlevel\fR
For analyzed images or PDFs, select \fIlow\fR (default), \fImedium\fR, or
\fIhigh\fR. Start at low and increase the level only when more detail is needed.
.TP
\fB--page\fR \fIpage\fR
For \fBread\fR, select a one-based PDF page. For \fBview\fR, restrict the
structural view to a one-based source page.
.TP
\fB--format\fR \fIformat\fR
For \fBdef\fR and \fBrefs\fR, select \fIjson\fR (default) or \fIplain\fR.
For \fBview\fR, select \fIplain\fR (default) or \fIjson\fR.
.TP
\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR
Cursor line for \fBrefs --scope\fR and \fBrename\fR.
.TP
\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR
One-based byte column for \fBidentify\fR or the cursor column for \fBrefs --scope\fR
and \fBrename\fR.
Identifier ranges in JSON use a one-based inclusive start column and a one-based
exclusive end column.
.TP
\fB--scope\fR
For \fBrefs\fR, resolve only the lexical binding under \fB--line\fR/\fB--column\fR
in a single file instead of matching every occurrence of the name.
.TP
\fB--to\fR \fIname\fR
For \fBrename\fR, the new name for the binding. Must be a plain identifier and
differ from the current name.
.TP
\fB--workspace\fR \fIdir\fR
For \fBrename\fR, expand the rename across \fIdir\fR. See \fBrename\fR under
\fBCOMMANDS\fR for cross-file matching and Git file selection.
.TP
\fB--apply\fR
Apply planned edits after checking conflicts and verifying affected files and line
hashes.
.TP
\fB--plan-hash\fR \fIhash\fR
For \fBrename --apply\fR, require the apply plan to match the hash emitted by an
earlier dry-run plan.
.TP
\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR
Last line to include when reading. Cannot be combined with \fB--limit\fR.
.TP
\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR
Maximum number of lines to include when reading. Cannot be combined with \fB--end\fR.
.TP
\fB--node\fR \fIid\fR
For \fBview\fR, use the indexed node ID as the view root.
.TP
\fB--kind\fR \fIkind\fR
For \fBview\fR, include only nodes of the selected kind: \fIartifact\fR,
\fIfooter\fR, \fIheader\fR, \fIheading\fR, \fImarginal_label\fR, \fIpage\fR,
\fIpage_number\fR, \fIparagraph\fR, \fIsection\fR, or
\fIstructural_section\fR.
.TP
\fB--depth\fR \fIn\fR
For \fBview\fR, limit output to this depth below the selected roots.
.TP
\fB--outline\fR
For \fBview\fR, return outline nodes only.
.TP
\fB\-g\fR, \fB--git\fR \fIscopes\fR
Comma-list of Git search scopes: \fBcached\fR (tracked and indexed
files), \fBothers\fR (untracked, non-ignored files), \fBignored\fR (ignored
untracked files; requires \fBothers\fR). Default is none.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B READSEEK_VISION_THREADS
Positive Rayon worker count for CPU inference. Rayon chooses the default.

.SH DIRECTORY SEARCH

\fBdef\fR, \fBrefs\fR, and \fBsearch\fR accept a file or recursively search a
directory. Inside a Git work tree, the default includes tracked/indexed and
untracked, non-ignored files. \fB--git cached\fR or \fB--git others\fR restricts the set.
Outside Git, \fB--git\fR is ignored and a normal recursive walk is used.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Operational error: file not found, binary input, malformed input, cache failure,
or symbol lookup failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error: incorrect invocation or argument combination.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I .readseek/maps/
Binary source-map cache files keyed by file hash.
.TP
.I .readseek/def-index/
Sharded binary definition index keyed by symbol name, used by \fBdef\fR directory lookup.
.TP
.I .readseek/documents/
Persistent PDF structural indexes and extracted embedded-image assets, keyed by
PDF content hash.
.TP
.I .readseek/vision/
Content-addressed, profile-specific cache of image captions, object detection, and
OCR results.
.TP
.I user cache directory/readseek/models/
The Qwen3-VL-2B Q8_0 model and multimodal projector, downloaded lazily and
checksum-verified for analyzed image modes.

.SH EXAMPLES

Detect the language of a file:
.EX
readseek detect src/main.rs
.EE

Read lines 10 through 20:
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs:10 --end 20
.EE

Read 12 lines starting from line 42:
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs:42 --limit 12
.EE

Read unsaved buffer text from standard input:
.EX
printf '%s\en' 'fn main() {}' | readseek read stdin:scratch.rs
.EE

Build a structural map of a file:
.EX
readseek map src/main.rs
.EE

View the structure of an indexed PDF page:
.EX
readseek view report.pdf --page 3
.EE

Look up a symbol by name or by the line it's on:
.EX
readseek symbol src/main.rs:run --name
readseek symbol src/main.rs:270
.EE

Identify what's under the cursor at line 42, column 8:
.EX
readseek identify src/main.rs:42 --column 8
.EE

Find definitions of a symbol in tracked files:
.EX
readseek def -c src run --language rust
.EE

Find references to a symbol in tracked files:
.EX
readseek refs -c src main --language rust
.EE

Search Rust functions with an AST pattern:
.EX
readseek search -c src 'fn $NAME() { $$$BODY }' --language rust
.EE

Plan a rename of the binding under the cursor:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed
.EE

Apply the rename to the file:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed --apply
.EE

Rename a symbol across the repository after verifying every affected file:
.EX
readseek rename src/main.rs --line 42 --column 8 --to renamed --workspace . --apply
.EE

Run captioning with four inference threads:
.EX
READSEEK_VISION_THREADS=4 readseek read photo.jpg --vision-mode caption --vision-level low
.EE

.SH BUILDING

Build from source:
.EX
cargo build --release
.EE
The Makefile also provides install and uninstall targets.

